## How the security requirements are met

- **SQL injection** — every query is a `better-sqlite3` parameterised prepared statement.
- **Passwords** — bcrypt (cost 12), salted; login uses constant-work compare + generic errors to avoid enumeration; session regenerated on login to stop fixation.
- **Access control / IDOR** — all file/share queries are filtered by `user_id`; a share token resolves to exactly one file and grants read-only download.
- **XSS** — EJS auto-escaping (`<%= %>`) + strict Helmet CSP with no inline scripts (I removed the one inline handler to keep CSP clean).
- **CSRF** — synchronizer token in every form, verified in constant time on all POSTs.
- **Cookies** — `HttpOnly`, `SameSite=Lax`, `Secure` when `COOKIE_SECURE=true`.
- **Headers / error handling** — Helmet headers; central error handler returns generic messages, never stack traces.
- **Secrets** — read only from env (`SESSION_SECRET`); fails fast in production if missing.
- **Upload hardening** — content-sniffed allow-list (PNG/JPG/GIF/WEBP/PDF), enforced max size (default 10 MiB), random server-generated storage names, files stored in a non-served `uploads/` dir, served as `attachment` + `nosniff`, and `resolveWithinUploads()` confines all reads to the upload directory (path-traversal guard).

