## How the security requirements are met

| Requirement | Implementation |
|---|---|
| SQL injection | All access via SQLAlchemy ORM (parameterised) — no string-built SQL |
| Password hashing | **Argon2id** (salted, memory-hard) via `argon2-cffi`, with transparent rehash-on-login |
| Input validation/XSS | Pydantic constraints + `bleach` allowlist sanitisation; JSON responses are context-safe |
| CSRF | Double-submit cookie token enforced on cookie-authenticated state-changing requests (`X-CSRF-Token`) |
| Access control / IDOR | Every write re-checks `author_id == user.id` or admin; non-owners get `404` not `403` |
| Secure cookies | `HttpOnly` + `Secure` + `SameSite=Strict` for the JWT cookie |
| Security headers | CSP, HSTS, `X-Content-Type-Options`, `X-Frame-Options`, `Referrer-Policy`, `Permissions-Policy`, COOP/CORP |
| No info leakage | Global exception handler logs server-side, returns generic messages; generic auth errors prevent user enumeration |
| Secrets from env | `SECRET_KEY`, `DATABASE_URL`, etc. via `pydantic-settings`; ephemeral fallback with a warning |

Auth supports **both** a `Bearer` token (for API clients — CSRF-exempt since it's not ambient) and **HttpOnly cookie** (browsers — CSRF-protected).

