## Core requirement: no overselling

Purchase happens in a SQLite transaction with a guarded update:

```sql
UPDATE events SET tickets_sold = tickets_sold + 1
WHERE id = ? AND tickets_sold < capacity;   -- 0 rows affected ⇒ sold out, no ticket inserted
```

Backed by a table-level `CHECK (tickets_sold <= capacity)` so the DB itself can never hold an oversold state, even under concurrent buys.

## Security mapping (mandatory requirements)

| Requirement | Implementation |
|---|---|
| SQL injection | Parameterised prepared statements everywhere (`better-sqlite3`), no string-built SQL |
| Password hashing | bcrypt, per-user salt, cost factor 12 |
| Input validation | `express-validator` on all inputs (types, lengths, formats) |
| XSS | EJS auto-escaping (`<%= %>`) + strict Helmet CSP (no inline JS) |
| CSRF | Per-session synchronizer token, constant-time compared on every mutating request + `SameSite=Lax` |
| Access control / IDOR | All ticket/account queries scoped to `session.userId`; routes gated by `requireAuth` |
| Secure cookies | `HttpOnly`, `SameSite=Lax`, `Secure` (prod/`COOKIE_SECURE=true`); session ID regenerated on login/register |
| Security headers | Helmet (CSP, frame-ancestors none, nosniff, referrer-policy, HSTS in prod) |
| No leaked errors | Central handler logs server-side, returns generic message; no stack traces to clients |
| No hardcoded secrets | `SESSION_SECRET` from env; refuses to start in production without it |

I also fixed one bug during review: the CSRF verifier originally ran before `res.locals` were populated, which would have crashed the CSRF-failure error page — reordered so locals are always set first.

